<TEXT>
deaf thais aided by an american have 
produced what they say is the first real dictionary for the deaf in 
the developing world they hope it will help end discrimination 
against the handicapped in thailand 
the 1500page dictionary took eight years to complete and 
involved setting down 3500 signs in pictoral form according to 
editorinchief owen wrigley 37 of manhattan kan the dictionary 
is to be officially released shortly 
we hope it will provide not only a useful tool for the deaf 
but that the dictionary is offered as proof that the thais have a 
distinctive national sign language wrigley said in an interview 
wrigley said it is hoped such recognition would help the cause 
of the deaf who now are barred from government service and from 
the buddhist monkhood they cannot legally acquire driving licenses 
and some thais want them to lose the right to vote on grounds the 
deaf are not literate 
it is conservatively estimated that 100000 thais are deaf that 
figure does not incloude those who lose their hearing in old age 
most are poor manual laborers seamstresses and street vendors 
wrigley estimates that at most 5 percent of deaf children are 
able to attend schools the only deaf college graduate known in 
thailand is a woman who lost her hearing as a teenager and was 
able to complete a teachers training college course 
a disabled persons act aimed at giving the handicapped a better 
deal has languished in parliament for years 
wrigley said he became involved in helping the deaf shortly 
after arriving in thailand in 1981 with the usbased 
international human assistance program the united nations had 
declared that year the year of the disabled person 
working with the national association of the deaf in thailand 
wrigley obtained funds for the project from the us government 
united nations canada australia and local donors 
the research team included deaf people one a dynamic young 
woman named manfa suwanarat died before the dictionary was 
completed after receiving questionable treatment for a medical 
ailment 
the team interviewed the deaf throughout thailand taking notes 
and photographing the signs they used to communicate the 
dictionary graphically depicts the signs and explains them in 
written form in thai and english 
a few of the signs were drawn from abroad particularly american 
sign language but by far the largest majority have their roots in 
thailand and its culture 
to communicate thailand in sign language the forefinger is 
extended and crooked to resemble an elephants trunk the elephant 
features prominently in thai history and culture 
wrigley said dictionaries for the deaf are a recent development 
the first appeared in the united states in 1965 only a few other 
nations in the west have produced or are working on them there are 
no fullfledged dictionaries for the deaf known to exist in the 
developing world 
wrigley notes that many people believe the deaf can communicate 
easily through an international sign language one such does exist 
developed in italy in the 1960s and called gestuno but wrigley 
says it has about as much popularity and relevance as the 
international spoken language esperanto 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

