<TEXT>
foy david kohler a career diplomat and the 
us ambassador to moscow during the height of the cold war died 
sunday at age 82 
kohler died at jupiter hospital after a long illness the 
hospital released no details on the cause of death 
kohler was ambassador to the soviet union from august 1962 to 
november 1966 he was considered a member of the realist school of 
international politics which emphasized the importance of 
military economic and political power in world affairs 
kohler first went to moscow in january 1947 as first secretary 
of the us embassy he was there when soviet leader nikita 
khrushchev and thenvice president richard nixon toured a model 
american kitchen during a 1959 american exposition in moscow 
khrushchev became angry and the kitchen debate between him 
and nixon drew international attention 
president john f kennedy tapped the russianspeaking diplomat 
to become ambassador to the soviet union in 1962 shortly after he 
arrived in moscow the cuban missile crisis erupted and brought the 
world to the brink of war 
kohler retired in 1967 then spent almost 11 years as a 
professor at the university of miamis graduate center for advanced 
international studies 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
donald eugene walters a former 
president of montclair state college died sunday of brain cancer 
at age 56 
he died at his home in cape cod mass 
walters was executive director of the illinois board of 
governors a body that runs several illinois state campuses from 
1975 to 1984 before that he been with the massachusetts state 
college system 
walters served as president of montclair from 1984 to 1988 when 
he retired because of illness 
</TEXT>
