<TEXT>
for the seventh time a court refused 
to order a hospital to resume feeding nancy cruzan the severely 
braininjured woman whose family won her right to die 
meanwhile on christmas eve eight antieuthanasia demonstrators 
huddled without their tent outside the building where she lay 
dying protesters have maintained a roundtheclock vigil since ms 
cruzans feeding tube was removed dec 14 
the court decision monday came in response to a request by the 
rev patrick j mahoney of boca raton fla who argued the state 
was violating ms cruzans rights by not ordering her to be fed 
the 8th us circuit court of appeals issued a onepage order 
that said mahoney had no standing in the case mahoney said he 
would take his case to the us supreme court 
the us district court for western missouri had earlier 
dismissed mahoneys suit 
ms cruzan has been in a persistent vegetative state since an 
auto crash in early 1983 doctors give her n chance of recovery 
she remained in deteriorating condition today 
also monday authorities ordered demonstrators outside the 
missouri rehabilitation center to remove a tent they had erected 
when protesters refused hospital employees took it down 
the demonstrators had been using a torch in the tent to combat 
the bonechilling weather the arrangement was considered a fire 
hazard and once temperatures warmed into the 20s monday hospital 
officials order it removed hospital director don lamkins said 
in a landmark ruling the us supreme court said earlier this 
year missouri could require clear and convincing evidence that 
a person in ms cruzans condition would want to die 
jasper county judge charles teel then heard testimony from 
friends who said ms cruzan would want to die and ruled her parents 
could have the feeding tube removed 
the latest appeals court ruling was the seventh time a court had 
refused to order feeding of ms cruzan resumed 
mahoneys motion said the state was violating ms cruzans 
rights and argued the hearing teel held was improper because 
witnesses who testified were not crossexamined and there were no 
witnesses who said ms cruzan should be kept alive 
mahoney also argued that the state had erred by not appealing 
teels order 
the clergyman filed his action under a legal concept called 
next of friend describing it as a strategy to be used when no 
one else was protecting the rights of a person 
in taking the case to the us supreme court mahoney said he 
would cite testimony from the former chaplain at the hospital who 
said ms cruzan had a noticeable reaction when he told her she was 
going to die 
unlike comatose patients ms cruzan opens her eyes and changes 
her facial expressions but doctors testified her lack of 
consciousness was irreversible and she had no awareness and could 
not feel pain 
mahoney is director of the center for christian activities a 
righttolife group associated with the antiabortion group 
operation rescue 
