<TEXT>
american airlines accused its pilots of staging a 
sickout during one of the busiest travel times of the year to 
protest stalled contract talks 
american based in forth worth said the number of pilots 
calling in sick over the weekend before christmas soared to record 
numbers the absentee rate was almost 70 percent higher than 
normal airline officials said 
union officials denied any organized protest was occurring but 
conceded that disgruntled employees could be acting on their own 
american management and the allied pilots association have been 
negotiating a contract for 14 months but have made little headway 
its all an attempt to compel the company to agree to terms 
that the pilots would like us to on the contract said robert w 
baker american executive vice president for operations 
baker said 529 of americans 9000 pilots were on sick leave 
monday about 500 pilots had called in sick over the weekend the 
pilot absentee rate is about 250 normally and 300 during christmas 
holidays american spokesman marty heires said 
we have to assume theres some union activity here heires 
said now i dont know whether this was an organized effort or 
whether some pilots are taking it upon themselves to do this 
all were seeing is the end result weve had an approximate 
67 percent increase in the number of pilots calling in sick he 
said 
union officials denied a concerted effort is behind the higher 
absentee rate 
i know theres nothing going on in terms of any grassroots 
operation or any other type of operation to call in sick or not 
being available aa executive director scott peterson said 
baker said the absentee rate for flight attendants was average 
the apparent pilot sickout coupled with bad weather a high 
volume of holiday traffic and the airlines loss of 230 pilots to 
operation desert shield led to an unusually high number of flight 
cancellations over the weekend heires said 
american canceled 74 flights or one in every 11 flights into 
and out of its hub at dallasfort worth international airport 
during sundays holiday crunch 
a sickout would be illegal under the railway labor act which 
also covers airlines 
both management and labor traded contract proposals in the past 
month but remain far apart negotiations resume jan 7 in 
washington under the auspices of federal mediators 
under the railway labor act the existing contract will remain 
in force until a federal mediator declares an impasse after a 
30day cooling off period the carrier may impose new terms on the 
pilots and the union can strike 
the union has been urging members to be diligent about seeking 
sick leave when ill and not to answer their phones if they dont 
want to work on their days off 
although the company may be disappointed in that theres 
nothing illegal about it said apa spokesman tom hunt whats 
the reason for that i think its low morale theres no question 
the pilots at american airlines are extremely disgruntled with the 
