the prospect of war in the middle east 
has military and civilian security forces making extra sure theyre 
ready to protect the 800milelong transalaska oil pipeline from 
terrorists 
americas most important oil lifeline also may be its most 
vulnerable far removed from the continental united states and 
surrounded by wilderness 
its safety rests largely on a private firm under contract to 
alyeska pipeline service co the consortium of oil companies 
running the pipeline with plans for support from alaska state 
troopers the alaska national guard and the air force officials 
said 
security along the pipeline at pump stations and the 1000acre 
tanker loading terminal in valdez was tightened after iraqs 
invasion of kuwait in august alyeska officials said 
beyond that security plans to combat terrorist threats are 
being upgraded at the request of sen ted stevens ralaska 
in august i raised the question several times about the 
status of the contingency plans for the protection of the 
pipeline stevens said lt gen thomas mcinerney commander of 
the 11th air force in alaska was involved in the talks he said 
im assured there have been some meetings that have explored 
the degree of cooperation and coordination necessary to defend 
the pipeline he said they have a good plan i asked them to 
dust it off and make sure everybody understood it 
the transalaska oil pipeline completed in 1977 is the jugular 
of domestic oil production about 2 million barrels a day of north 
slope crude one quarter of all us output is pumped from 
prudhoe bay fields to the icefree port of valdez 
alyeska national guard and other federal officials would not 
discuss specific aspects of pipeline security saying it reveal too 
much to terrorists 
we are working on a draft plan national guard spokeswoman 
kristine schuster said alyeska is the lead agency here the 
national guard has been asked to give their input 
i dont talk about it said jp pat wellington manager 
of corporate security for alyeska he oversees alyeskas contract 
with american guard alert inc which is in charge of physical 
security on the 9 billion pipeline 
we are aware of what the security plans are and we are happy 
with them said dave vickery spokesman for the us bureau of 
land management which with the federal department of 
transportation and the state division of natural resources monitors 
the pipeline 
the 48inch pipe half of it buried and half of it elevated was 
laid across 575 miles of blmmanaged land it crosses 34 major 
rivers and 800 smaller streams seventythousand people helped 
build it 
at least two telephone threats warning of possible attacks on 
the pipeline were reported in recent weeks but neither claim could 
be substantiated and officials declined to discuss them 
its our policy not to confirm or deny the receipt of 
threats said tom matthews chief fbi agent in alaska 
meanwhile a source familiar with alyeska security who asked not 
to be identified said the pipeline company has been considering 
subscribing to a terrorism forecasting service 
despite the official worries terrorism specialist mike ackerman 
of ackerman associates in miami said the pipeline is an unlikely 
target of arab extremists 
terrorists if they strike inside the us would probably hit 
public targets such as airports in detroit or new york city 
ackerman said 
and a possible attack on the pipeline would be unlikely to shut 
down oil flow for a significant period of time he said 
