<TEXT>
when electric rates go up or the wind 
knocks power lines down norman pearson and julieanne belanger 
never notice 
pearson and belanger choose to live without any help from the 
electric company they heat their home with wood and cook with 
propane or on a wood stove depending on the season 
until last spring when pearson installed solar panels on his 
roof that provide some electricity the only indoor lighting was 
from gas lamps kerosene lanterns and flashlights 
the couple do without indoor plumbing and use an outhouse 20 
yards from their home 
pearson who grew up in a middleclass home in a chicago suburb 
says he enjoys the feeling of selfsufficiency 
his decision to go without electricity also reflects his 
opposition to nuclear power and concern that extending power lines 
to his house might encourage people to build on undeveloped 
property nearby 
ive seen power bills said pearson im amazed at how 
much they are 
its a secure thing said belanger who built a tiny house 
of her own in nearby concord with no water or electricity in the 
1970s our neighbors sometimes would call after a storm and say 
did you lose your electricity theyd forget 
pearson and belanger are not the only people in maine who live 
without electricity there are houses scattered around the state 
without power although there are no statistics on how many 
the couples house looks as if it were built in sections as 
needed there are no visible wires leading to the house the phone 
line is underground 
inside the house is heated by a wood stove and the sun that 
shines through fiberglass covers on the southern side pearson cuts 
the wood on his land primarily from damaged trees to feed the 
stove 
more than seven cords of wood enough to last more than a year 
are stacked in a shed 
its a great feeling to have excess wood pearson said 
the couple cook on a big castiron woodburning stove during 
the summer they use a small stove hooked up to a propane gas tank 
their tiny refrigerator is powered by propane in the summer and is 
not used in the winter 
the only water inside comes through a hand pump in the kitchen 
sink hooked up to a well theres no toilet no shower no hot 
water except for the pot on top of the stove 
pearson said he could build a bathroom but prefers the 
outhouse toilets waste too much clean water he says 
pearson grew up with the typical amenities and graduated from 
northwestern university he was a maine social worker for seven 
years and now works six to eight weeks a year as a substitute rural 
mail carrier he is also a new vineyard selectman 
belanger teaches first grade in new portland 10 miles away her 
daughter ahmen is an eighthgrader at mount blue junior high 
school in farmington 
ahmen would prefer to live in a normal house with electricity 
and water she said she would love to have a shower in the 
mornings and isnt fond of having to walk to the outhouse 
especially on cold winter nights 
many of her friends think the house is novel but others refuse 
to visit overnight because theres no bathroom 
pearson said his lifestyle has surprised foreign friends who 
have visited the house over the years 
they were amazed pearson said they always thought 
america is the land of consumption the land of plenty 
