<TEXT>
american airlines charges that its pilots are 
staging a sickout over stalled contract talks and have contributed 
to flight cancellations but the pilots union denies theres any 
organized protest 
american management and the allied pilots association have been 
negotiating a revsed contract for 14 months but have made little 
headway 
the increase in the number of pilots calling in sick coupled 
with bad weather the holiday traffic crush and the airlines loss 
of 230 pilots to operation desert shield led to an unusually high 
number of flight cancellations over the weekend said american 
spokesman marty heires 
at its hub at dallasfort worth international airport on sunday 
the carrier canceled 37 arriving and 37 departing flights 
amounting to about 9 percent of its flights 
the fort worthbased carrier said the number of pilots calling 
in sick over the weekend soared to record numbers almost 70 
percent higher than normal airline officials said 
its all an attempt to compel the company to agree to terms 
that the pilots would like us to on the contract said robert w 
baker american executive vice president for operations 
baker told the dallas morning news in tuesdays editions that 
529 of americans 9000 pilots were on sick leave monday and about 
500 called in sick over the weekend 
the typical pilot absentee rate is 250 during normal periods and 
300 during christmas holidays said heires 
we have to assume theres some union activity here heires 
said now i dont know whether this was an organized effort or 
whether some pilots are taking it upon themselves to do this 
union officials denied any concerted effort was behind the 
higher absentee rate though for some time now they have been 
urging pilots not to work if they are sick 
i know theres nothing going on in terms of any grassroots 
operation or any other type of operation to call in sick or not 
being available said apa executive director scott peterson 
baker said the absentee rate for flight attendants is average 
both management and labor traded contract proposals in the past 
month but remain far apart negotiations resume jan 7 in 
washington dc under the auspices of the national mediation 
board 
under the railway labor act the existing contract will remain 
in force until a federal mediator declares an impasse after a 
30day cooling off period the carrier may impose new conditions of 
employment on the pilots and the union can strike 
employee sickouts are illegal under the railway labor act 
for several months the union has been urging its members not to 
push themselves into going to work if they are ill and not to 
answer their phones if they dont want to work on their days off 
the union says that does not amount to a sickout 
although the company may be disappointed in that theres 
nothing illegal about it said apa spokesman tom hunt whats 
the reason for that i think its low morale theres no question 
the pilots at american airlines are extremely disgruntled with the 
company with management 
the apa is seeking to abolish the twotier wage scale pilots 
accepted in 1983 when the company was struggling financially the 
twotier scale pays newly hired pilots at a lower scale than 
existing crew members 
in addition union members want the company to bring newer 
pilots up to parity in terms of pension and vacation time the 
pilots are also fighting the companys insistence that they 
shoulder a greater share of their health care insurance costs 
apa members also contend that american as the largest airline 
in the western world and one of the most profitable should pay its 
pilots the highest wage of any us airline 
the company contends the apas contract demands will force it to 
scale back its fiveyear 209 billion expansion plan 
