<TEXT>
for many of the nations retailers the 
christmas shopping season was a disappointing casualty of the 
recession and the middle east crisis despite a lastminute burst 
of business from procrastinating consumers 
some retailers were heartened by a late pickup in their sales 
others smarting from the poor season were looking ahead to gloomy 
times early next year 
sears roebuck and co the nations largest retailer was among 
those whose sales were hurt this season by consumer worries about 
the economy and the middle east 
were slightly below expectations matthew howard sears 
senior vice president for marketing said monday evening as the 
christmas season drew to a close 
however sears took comfort from its results the last three days 
of the season when shoppers responded to a new advertising 
campaign and a new round of price reductions on a variety of 
merchandise 
were pleased we felt we got a good balance in all of the 
businesses howard said in a telephone interview the final 
weekend left sears inventories in good shape he said 
other highprofile retailers reported a lastminute surge in 
sales but as in sears case the extra business was not enough to 
turn the entire season around 
there was a bit of a rush that was encouraging but as you 
know prior to this weekend it had been pretty sluggish said 
suzanne mcmillan senior vice president for marketing at the 
upscale saks fifth avenue 
at dayton hudson corp chairman kenneth macke was clearly 
disappointed with the season 
when all the receipts are tallied dayton hudsons sales will be 
unchanged to 1 percent higher than the firms christmas 1989 
results macke said monday afternoon 
im not feeling very happy he said 
sales that are little changed or up very slightly are considered 
poor because when the effects of inflation are subtracted a 
stores business may be down from yearearlier levels consumer 
prices rose 64 percent through the first 11 months of this year 
meaning many stores modest gains were wiped out 
predictions of a poor christmas season were issued back in 
august as sales of clothing furniture toys and appliances stalled 
in the wake of the iraqi invasion of kuwait 
sales for most retailers did not recover in september october 
and november normally a time when their business accelerates 
after the christmas season kicked off in late november store 
traffic and sales generally remained slow until the final weekend 
the weather also worked against the retailers this christmas in 
some parts of the midwest snow and ice kept shoppers at home but 
in many other areas temperatures in the 50s and 60s curbed sales 
of winter clothing 
